Oh not very long. I wasn't very long at all - I don't remember. Then I stayed home for a bit. And I think the war must have been starting to break out then you see I think - 1914 you see, the war and - beginning
 of the war there wouldn't be - I wasn't working when the war started I know. - And then - they wanted volunteers to go and work in - in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5077625\charrsid2650350 munitions}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13519019\charrsid2650350  works. We all thought we were going voluntary and we went to the Cnard to - to tend shells - forgotten wh
at we were called and - we did shift work. Well I don't know if the Cunard weren't going to pay us but the government paid us and we got - we did three shirts, seven - to two, two 'til ten and ten to seven and when you were on the day shifts you got a pou
n
d a week with things knocked off - tuppence ha'penny because you were put in the trade union, threepence for Lloyd George and so much for your meals - they gave us very good meals and when you worked all night you got twenty-five shillings. And I was ther
e - oh I must have been there about six months and the doctor stopped me going. 'Cos I lost a lot of weight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14045772\charrsid2650350 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13519019\charrsid2650350 
How did you feel about that job - how did you get on with the other people?
